ily of UK AONBs as Category V Protected Landscape</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s by the IUCN.  The North Wessex Downs AONB Partnership is currently a partner, advisor or supporter in a range</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of conservation projects, both large scale (incl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rlborough Do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ns </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Nature</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Imp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">v</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ment Area, Stepping Stones</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Winni</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g Ways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for Wildlife</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d the South West Farmland Bird Initiative) and small, community- and farm-based activity.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We also engage very closely in land use planning of the AONB, providing landscape-related advice to land owners, developers, local authorities, parish councils, N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">GOs, community groups and individuals.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This submission draws on reading and discussion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the Government’s published Gr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">en Paper on biodiversity offsetting.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are sceptical about the motivation behind the Green Paper proposals.  It seems unlikely that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a system of biodiversity offsetting could make dealing with wildlife in planning system easier, cheaper and quick for developers whilst also delivering significant extra benefits for wildlife. This is not to rule out the potential benefits of some sort of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> system of offsetting; it already takes place, albeit with great variations in success.  However, the Green Paper proposals would need to be improved beyond recognition and offsets would have to be the option of very last resort, after rigorous attention t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o avoidance and mitigation had failed to achieve what was needed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Offsetting needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o be seen </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the context of the other factors we consider when trying to judge whether or not the public interest is served by a particular proposal.  As a society, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e rightly cherish some of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r most historic buildings.  Were devel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pers to prop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se demol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ishing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lisbury Cathedral we would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be unlikely to deem it a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cceptable pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed they built three replica cathedrals to offset the loss.  While the imp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce of hist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ric</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> value, cultural resonance and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">location in this example do not apply to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all wildlife or habitats</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, they do in very many.  Numerous biodiversity assets are basically irreplaceable, bound up as they are with the location and the human experience of those plac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es.  We should not pretend that by commoditising biodiversity with a standard metric we are taking proper account of these highly complicated and unique factors on any given site.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How can it account for u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">niqueness</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  Every place and asset is unique.  O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fsetting to enable substitution of biodiversity value lost, e.g. through development, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is unlikely to compensate for other aspects of a site.  Location is the most obvious, but topography, history, cultural and social value are also difficult</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> if not imposs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to substitute for.  A mature hedge might</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">conceivably, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be replaced by something providing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">comparable wildlife habitat, albeit only after many years has passed, but the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">400 year-old </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hedge bank is irreplaceable.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Green Paper suggests loss of a high</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> quality hedge should be offset by planting a new hedge three times the length of that lost.  This does not seem an adequate response.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Can it reliably ensure the benefits endure p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ermanen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">tly?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Among current proposals for offsetting, especially the mooted n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ational system of credits, it is been suggested that credits should last for 25 years, with 99 years being defined as “permanent”.  This would be wholly inadequate to the scale and importance of the task.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Much habitat is the legacy of centuries of consist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent management.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If offsetting is to be meaningful</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and command public confidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, any replacement sites would need to be safeguarded in perpetuity.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This raises extremely difficult questions, for example of mapping, monitoring, legal enforcement, resilienc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e, and long-term management through changes of ownership.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How can the benefits be e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nforce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">d, by whom and who will pay?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  The proposal for a system of biodiversity offsetting raises the prospect of a need for a new nationwide system of consistent monitoring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and enforcement.  Enforcement is the poor relation in planning and development, with some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local authorities admitting that they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hardly do </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– a result of the absence of any fee income and correspondingly low political priority.  Wildlife habitat, dynamic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and requiring management, is likely to require significantly more enforcement than built development and over a much longer period (essentially permanently).  This will require resources and expertise and hence funding, which presumably those purchasing th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e offsets will need to pay for. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Can it avoid p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">rejudicing decisions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is very difficult to see how the existence of an offsetting system could do other than prejudice decision making on development proposals.  However, f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or the integrity of the planning system to remain intact it would be essential that any system of offsetting had no influence on decision-making on development proposals.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">withdrawal of wildlife impact from the factors under consideration (e.g. on a pl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">anning application), on the basis that this could be accounted for through offsets, would inevitably reduce the collective weight of factors suggesting that a harmful development would not be in the wider public interest.  This would apply especially to im</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pacts closely associated with the biodiversity value that were unique to a site (see Uniqueness above).  This risks resulting in more decisions harmful to the unique value of individual sites, even if general biodiversity harm could be offset.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Can it over</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">come the p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ractical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> difficulties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While in theory we know all the components necessary to restore or recreate certain habitats, the desired result does not just happen if the components are brought together.  The reality is far more complex and difficult. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Location, geology, climate and host of other variables combine unpredictably.  Simplistic metrics such as those proposed in the biodiversity offsetting green paper will not be sufficient to achieve what is desired.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Connectivity of habitats – how one site</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> relates to those around it – is critical to successful conservation and enhancement.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Despite increasing recognition of this, by Sir John Lawton and the Government among others, connectivity is not adequately addressed in the Green Paper.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Any system of o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ffsetting needs convincingly and robustly to build connectivity into its workings, informed by t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he expertise of organisations with many years’ experience of habitat restoration, such as Flora Locale.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We offer the following as a (far from exhaustive) list </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">requirements </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that any</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> viable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, enduring</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">publicly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">credible system of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> biodiversity offsetting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> would need to meet.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Any system of offsetting needs to recognise the uniqueness and irreplaceability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of every individual site, including non-biodiversity aspects that are often bound up with biodiversity such as historic, social and cultural value.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Offsetting must not prejudice planning decisions.  Offsets must only be used as a last resort, where optio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ns for avoiding and mitigating biodiversity harm have been exhaustively explored and the proposal is in the wider public interest having regard to all other material considerations.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Offsets must be in perpetuity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Offsets should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as far as possible </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be like</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">like.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  Where this is not possible, offsetting should not be contemplated.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It should not be possible, as is proposed in the Green Paper, for the grant of planning permission to strike out an offsetting commitment.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The system must be overseen, regulat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed, monitored and enforced by an independent, national (and international?) body.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  This body must be properly resourced without dependence on developer contributions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Effective sanctions must be available to punish and rectify failure to deliver or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">maintain offsets.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The system needs to incorporate robust safeguards against landowners destroying the value of (especially undesignated) sites prior to bringing forward development proposals.  Otherwise it could create a strong perverse incentive.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Develo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pment proposals and accompanying offsets need to take full account of existing and potential connectivity of habitat within the landscape.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The metric needs to take account of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">potential</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> biodiversity value of a site, not merely its value at the moment o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f application.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The metric needs to avoid simplistic equations of habitat gain and loss.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the suggestion in the Green Paper that a high quality hedgerow may be “replaced” with a newly pla</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ted hedge three time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the length of that lost.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">15 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>